BR.label: T0.choices.BR.label
BR.description: Black bears are large and heavily built.  They are usually black in color with a brown muzzle. Other uncommon color variations include brown or cinnamon. They have a short tail and prominent, round ears.

CT.label: T0.choices.CT.label

confusions.WLF: Wolf shown here. The gray wolf is the largest of wild canid species. Their fur is typically a mix of tan, brown, black, and cinnamon. Other uncommon color variations include both solid black and white. Wolves have a distinctive blocky muzzle with rounded, relatively short ears.

CT.description: This canid is shorter and lighter than a gray wolf. Their fur is typically a mix of tan, brown, black, and cinnamon. Coyotes have a distinctive pointed muzzle and pointed ears, which are large in proportion to the head.

DR.label: T0.choices.DR.label

DR.description: Lightly built, whitetail deer are grayish brown to reddish brown in color. The underside of their short tail is white.  Males have antlers which fork off a main branch and the young are reddish brown in color with white spots.

confusions.MSKRT: Muskrat shown here. The body of a muskrat is stout with dark brown fur. Muskrats have short rounded ears, barely protruding above the fur, and a rounded, scaly tail. They are typically found near water.

BVR.description: Beavers have glossy fur that can appear reddish brown to blackish brown. They have a distinctive scaly paddle-shape tail. They have short, round ears and are typically found near water.

CGR.label: T0.choices.CGR.label

confusions.LNX: Lynx shown here. The coat of this cat varies from gray to grayish brown with spots on the legs and belly. The lynx has long black tuffs on the ears. They have short tails that are tipped black. In comparison to a bobcat, lynx have very large furry feet and long legs. Lynx are very uncommon in Wisconsin, although rare sightings of visitors from Canada do occur.

Their head is relatively small and the area behind the ears is black. Cougars have a long black-tipped tail. Although there are no known breeding populations of cougar in Wisconsin, there have been several verified sightings in recent years.

GRS.label: T0.choices.GRS.label
GRS.description: Wisconsin is home to both spruce grouse and ruffed grouse. Both can appear red or gray in color. Ruffed grouse have a small crest on the top of the head with a black ruff on the sides of the neck. Male spruce grouse have a dark throat and breast.

PGFRL.description: Feral pigs or wild hogs are stocky animals and can vary greatly in size and color. Compared to domestic swine, they have longer snouts, longer course hair, a straight tail, and may have tusks. This exotic species is not common in Wisconsin.

PRCPN.label: T0.choices.PRCPN.label
PRCPN.description: The body of a porcupine is stout and covered in quills, which are partially concealed by long guard hairs. Porcupines appear dark brown in color.

SKNKSPTTD.description: This skunk is smaller than a striped skunk. It is black with a white patch on the forehead.
